The paper proposes a novel feature-driven active framework for ultrasound-based brain shift compensation. The method involves estimating landmarks and their displacement from a pair of ultrasound images using local image features, and then using a Gaussian Process model to interpolate a dense deformation field from the sparse landmarks. The paper involves computer vision (image feature extraction), robotics (neurosurgery), artificial intelligence (Gaussian Process model), machine learning (kernel estimation), and neural networks (variograms). Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), followed by cs.RO (Robotics), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.LG (Machine Learning), and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
